KlippyAI README Mirror
======================

This file exists because the project request explicitly asked for `README.mf`.
The primary project documentation remains `README.md`.

Summary
-------

KlippyAI is a Moonraker-integrated assistant for Klipper and Kalico printers.
It is intended to help users diagnose printer problems, understand logs and configuration issues, and eventually generate safe, reviewable config changes from within the printer web interface.

The chosen architecture is:

- standalone host daemon
- Moonraker as the printer-facing integration layer
- supported Mainsail custom-navigation link in `v1`
- same-origin KlippyAI UI at `/klippyai/`

What the project aims to achieve
--------------------------------

- inspect `klippy.log`, `moonraker.log`, and host-side logs
- detect common printer and service failures
- explain likely root causes and safer next steps
- help users define Klipper configs from a UI workflow
- keep provider API keys on the server side only

Current state
-------------

The repository currently contains an initial scaffold:

- FastAPI agent service
- Moonraker client abstraction
- full-page and embedded chat UI
- LangGraph diagnostics workflow skeleton
- OpenAI integration path through LangChain
- deterministic diagnostics rule engine
- host-side `klippy.log*` and `moonraker.log*` collection, intended to work with both long-lived logs and rotated restart archives
- `systemctl` and `journalctl` diagnostics for the Moonraker and Klipper services
- one-time printer-profile detection during install, persisted into `klippyai.cfg`
- firmware flavor detection for mainline Klipper, Kalico, and custom forks
- addon and hardware hint detection for common probes, CAN toolhead boards, and companion services
- persisted capability and geometry detection for probe type, accelerometer, filament sensor, build volume, extruder count, bed mesh, and input shaper state
- diagnostics prompts now include the current config tree alongside logs and the saved profile
- a config assistant path that inspects current config files and can generate first-pass proposals across common config categories
- config collection now follows the active root config include tree by default and can be overridden from `[config_context]`
- systemd and nginx deployment examples
- guided Linux `install.sh` installer
- installer support for a Mainsail custom-navigation link
- an optional Mainsail source patch bundle for advanced installs

What is not finished yet:

- real Moonraker agent registration
- broader host diagnostics beyond the current Moonraker/Klipper service scope
- config diff/apply flow and deeper specialization beyond the current scaffold-generation path
- broader LLM provider support

Installation
------------

On a Linux Klipper host:

1. Clone the repository onto the host.
2. Run:

   `chmod +x install.sh`

   `./install.sh`

   To remove the host install later:

   `chmod +x uninstall.sh`

   `./uninstall.sh`

3. The installer will prompt for:
   - service user
   - checkout path, default `/home/<service-user>/KlippyAI`
   - Moonraker URL, default `http://127.0.0.1:7125`
   - printer data root, default `/home/<service-user>/printer_data`
   - Mainsail config directory, default `/home/<service-user>/printer_data/config`
   - LLM provider
   - API key
   - model name
4. The installer then:
   - creates a Python virtual environment
   - installs the package
   - writes `/etc/klippyai/klippyai.env`
   - writes `printer_data/config/klippyai.cfg`
   - detects printer profile data once and stores it in `[printer_identity]`, `[printer_capabilities]`, and `[printer_geometry]`
   - writes `klippyai-moonraker.cfg` next to `moonraker.conf`
   - appends an include to `moonraker.conf`
   - adds `klippyai-agent` to `printer_data/moonraker.asvc`
   - creates a `systemd` service
   - generates an nginx snippet for `/klippyai/`
   - can write `.theme/navi.json` for a supported Mainsail link

The installer still asks for the service user first. The suggested checkout and printer-data paths are then derived from that user, so hosts using `biqu` will default to `/home/biqu/...`.

Important notes:

- the installer currently generates the nginx location snippet, but you still need to include it in the Mainsail nginx server block
- add this line to the Mainsail nginx server block:
  `include /etc/klippyai/nginx-location.conf;`
- common file locations are often:
  - `/etc/nginx/conf.d/mainsail.conf`
  - `/etc/nginx/sites-enabled/mainsail`
  - `/etc/nginx/sites-available/mainsail`
- the installer can also write `.theme/navi.json` so Mainsail shows a supported `KlippyAI` link
- normal runtime settings now live in `printer_data/config/klippyai.cfg`, intended to be editable from Mainsail
- `[printer_identity]`, `[printer_capabilities]`, and `[printer_geometry]` are auto-populated once during install
- `mainboard` and `toolhead` can be edited under `[printer_identity]` in `klippyai.cfg` to override detected values later
- capability fields like `probe_type`, `filament_sensor`, and `accelerometer` are persisted explicitly, including `none` when KlippyAI does not detect that hardware
- `[config_context]` lets you override `root_config_file` and optionally set `ignore_globs` for KlippyAI context collection
- if you want to rerun the one-time detection later, activate the venv and run `klippyai-detect-profile --config-file /home/<service-user>/printer_data/config/klippyai.cfg --moonraker-url http://127.0.0.1:7125 --printer-data-root /home/<service-user>/printer_data --overwrite`
- after editing `klippyai.cfg`, restart the service with `sudo systemctl restart klippyai-agent`
- `printer_data/moonraker.asvc` is what allows Moonraker and Mainsail to restart `klippyai-agent`
- after installation, restart Moonraker so it reloads the KlippyAI include and allowed-services file
- the installer does not patch or build Mainsail automatically
- the source patch bundle under `integrations/mainsail/` is optional, not the default v1 path

During uninstall, remove this line from the Mainsail nginx server block if it is still present:

`include /etc/klippyai/nginx-location.conf;`

Mainsail integration
--------------------

The recommended v1 integration is a Mainsail custom-navigation entry that links to:

`/klippyai/`

The repo includes:

- `integrations/mainsail/install-custom-nav.sh`
- `integrations/mainsail/navi.json.example`

Optional native patch
---------------------

The repo now includes:

- `integrations/mainsail/patches/mainsail-v2.17.0-klippyai-shell.patch`
- `integrations/mainsail/apply-patch.sh`
- `integrations/mainsail/README.md`

That patch currently targets upstream `mainsail-crew/mainsail` `develop` commit:

`6130a0aa1776a138feaab691b9e4b1334b676b79`

It adds:

- a KlippyAI launcher button in the Mainsail topbar
- a native right-side drawer shell
- bootstrap via `POST /klippyai/api/ui-sessions`
- an embedded iframe for the assistant UI

Features and direction
----------------------

Diagnostics:

- log analysis
- deterministic issue detection
- LLM-assisted explanations
- typed next-step recommendations

Config assistance:

- explain config options
- propose new config snippets
- evolve toward diff-based change review

Security:

- API keys should remain server-side only
- write actions should require explicit approval

Further details, repository layout, and roadmap are documented in `README.md`, `BACKLOG.md`, and `integrations/mainsail/README.md`.
